# TypeScript Best Practices

> Project style is enforced by ESLint + Prettier (`prettier/prettier: error`): **2-space indent, double quotes, semicolons**. Run `npm run lint` to check (add `--fix`, i.e. `npx eslint . --ext .ts,.js --fix`, to auto-correct) and `npm run typecheck` (`tsc --noEmit`) before committing. Examples below follow the project style.

## 1. Always Await Async Calls — No Floating Promises

Every `async` call must be `await`ed or explicitly handled. Floating promises silently swallow errors and create flaky tests.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — floating promise, error is swallowed
async function loadPage() {
  this.page.goto("/home"); // not awaited
  someAsyncSetup(); // not awaited
}

// ✅ GOOD
async function loadPage() {
  await this.page.goto("/home");
  await someAsyncSetup();
}
```

> Not currently lint-enforced (`@typescript-eslint/no-floating-promises` is not enabled in `.eslintrc.js`), but treat it as mandatory. Consider enabling the type-checked rule set to catch these automatically.

## 2. Return-Await in Async Functions

Prefer `return await` inside async functions. Omitting `await` on a `return` means errors in the returned promise are lost from the stack trace.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — if getCurrentUrl() throws, the stack trace skips this function
async function getCurrentUrl(): Promise<string> {
  return this.page.url();
}

// ✅ GOOD — the async frame is preserved in the stack trace
async function getCurrentUrl(): Promise<string> {
  return await this.page.url();
}
```

## 3. Small, Focused Interfaces — One Concern Per Interface (SRP)

Define typed interfaces for multi-field data passed to methods. Keep them small and single-purpose. Do not create large "god" interfaces that accumulate unrelated fields over time (YAGNI). Test-data shapes live in `data/types/` (e.g. `data/types/TestData.ts`).

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — raw string parameters, no type safety
// (see SamplePage.fillForm — a good candidate to refactor into an interface)
async fillForm(name: string, email: string, website: string, experience: string, comment: string) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — typed interface, self-documenting, reusable
export interface TestData {
  name: string;
  email: string;
  website: string;
  experience: string;
  comment: string;
}

async fillForm(data: TestData) { ... }
```

## 4. Use Guard Clauses to Avoid Deep Nesting (KISS)

Fail fast at the top of a function instead of wrapping the happy path in deeply nested `if/else` blocks.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — happy path buried in nesting
function processResult(result: string | null) {
  if (result) {
    if (result.length > 0) {
      doSomething(result);
    }
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD — guard clauses, flat structure
function processResult(result: string | null) {
  if (!result) return;
  if (result.length === 0) return;
  doSomething(result);
}
```

When a required dependency is missing, throw — never silently skip, or the test passes vacuously:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — assertion is skipped if the element was never resolved
if (locator != undefined) {
  await expect(locator).toBeVisible();
}

// ✅ GOOD — fails immediately with a clear, actionable error
if (!locator) {
  throw new Error("locator not initialized. Did the page object construct it?");
}
await expect(locator).toBeVisible();
```

## 5. Eliminate Duplication with a Lookup Map (DRY)

Replace repeated `if/else if` chains that map a key to a value with a lookup object.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — duplicated structure, hard to extend
private getMenu(name: string): Locator {
  if (name === "About") return this.aboutMenu;
  else if (name === "Contact Us") return this.contactUsMenu;
  else throw new Error(`Unknown menu: ${name}`);
}

// ✅ GOOD — lookup map, O(1), trivially extendable
type MenuName = "About" | "Cheatsheets" | "Contact Us";

private menuMap: Record<MenuName, Locator>;

constructor(page: Page) {
  super(page);
  this.menuMap = {
    About: this.page.locator("#menu a", { hasText: "About" }),
    Cheatsheets: this.page.locator("#menu a", { hasText: "Cheatsheets" }),
    "Contact Us": this.page.locator("#menu a", { hasText: "Contact Us" }),
  };
}

private getMenu(name: MenuName): Locator {
  const menu = this.menuMap[name];
  if (!menu) throw new Error(`Unknown menu: ${name}`);
  return menu;
}
```

## 6. Prefer `const` Over `let` (Immutability by Default)

Declare variables with `const` unless you explicitly need to reassign. It signals intent and prevents accidental mutation.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
let url = process.env.BASE_URL;
let timeout = 15000;

// ✅ GOOD
const url = process.env.BASE_URL;
const timeout = 15000;
```

## 7. No `any` Without Justification

`any` disables type checking silently. Use `unknown` when the type is genuinely uncertain and narrow it with a type guard, or use the correct specific type.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function parseResult(data: any) {
  return data.value;
}

// ✅ GOOD — unknown + type guard
function parseResult(data: unknown): string {
  if (typeof data === "object" && data !== null && "value" in data) {
    return String((data as { value: unknown }).value);
  }
  throw new Error("Unexpected result shape");
}
```

## 8. Use Union Types Instead of Raw Strings for Known Sets (KISS)

When a parameter can only be one of a known set of values, use a union type instead of `string`. This catches typos at compile time.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — any string accepted, typos silently fail
async function answerQuestion(answer: string) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — constrained to valid values
type YesNo = "Yes" | "No";
async function answerQuestion(answer: YesNo) { ... }
```

## 9. Centralize Environment Configuration

Environment variables are loaded by `dotenv` in `playwright.config.ts` (`dotenv.config()`). The base URL is wired into Playwright via `use.baseURL = process.env.BASE_URL`, so page objects should navigate with **relative paths** (`page.goto("/")`) and let Playwright resolve the base URL — don't hard-code full URLs or scatter `process.env` reads through page objects and specs.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — hard-coded host, bypasses baseURL config
await this.page.goto("https://www.globalsqa.com/samplepagetest/");

// ✅ GOOD — relative path resolves against use.baseURL from playwright.config.ts
await this.page.goto("/samplepagetest/", { waitUntil: "domcontentloaded" });
```

Keep raw `process.env` access in config/setup files (`playwright.config.ts`, `utils/globalSetup.ts`, `tests/auth.setup.ts`). When adding a new variable, also add it (blank value) to `.env.copy` so the contract is documented.

## 10. No Single-Use Local Variables — Inline Directly (KISS)

If a `const` is assigned once and then used exactly once in the same method, remove it and chain the call inline. The intermediate variable adds lines without adding clarity.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — `dropdown` is created only to be used on the very next line
async selectExperience(experience: string): Promise<void> {
  const dropdown = this.page.getByLabel("Experience");
  await dropdown.selectOption(experience);
}

// ✅ GOOD — chain directly; no intermediate variable needed
async selectExperience(experience: string): Promise<void> {
  await this.page.getByLabel("Experience").selectOption(experience);
}
```

**When a local variable IS appropriate:**

- It is referenced **two or more times** in the same method — naming it avoids repeating a long expression.
- It meaningfully improves readability by giving a complex expression a domain name.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — `baseContainer` used three times; variable prevents repetition
async toggleSwitchBox(selector: string, toggled: boolean) {
  const baseContainer = this.page.locator(selector);
  await expect(baseContainer).toBeVisible();
  const toggledOn = await baseContainer.locator('[class*="switch-off"]').isHidden();
  if (toggledOn != toggled) {
    await baseContainer.locator('[class*="switch-"]').click();
  }
}
```

## 11. Don't Add What You Don't Need (YAGNI)

Don't build abstractions, parameters, or utilities speculatively. Add them when a second real use case exists.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — "just in case" parameter that nothing uses yet
async clickSubmit(options?: { waitForNavigation?: boolean; retries?: number }) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — simple until complexity is actually needed
async submitForm() {
  await this.page.getByRole("button", { name: "Submit" }).click();
}
```

## 12. No Unused Imports or Variables

Remove all imports and variables that are declared but never used. They create noise and trigger `@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars` (currently `warn` in `.eslintrc.js`).

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — unused import and unused variable
import { Page, Locator, Download } from "@playwright/test"; // Download unused

async function run() {
  const unused = "never read";
  await doWork();
}

// ✅ GOOD — only what is actually used
import { Page, Locator } from "@playwright/test";

async function run() {
  await doWork();
}
```

